And so, here this\nbecomes a wicked problem.
And I was reading\nrecently a piece
by Pratap Bhanu Mehta, who is an\nIndian commentator, economist,
I think.
And just to quote\nfrom him, he said,
"In a society driven\nby deep inequality,
there's not even a minimal\nbasis for mutual concern.
Where social distance\nmakes human beings
almost a different species\nin each other's eyes,
why would you expect\nanything else?
Why would a contractor care if\none of his construction workers
used his hands\nrather than a brush
to apply a dangerous chemical?
The more inequality\nthere is, the harder
it is to imagine what it's like\nto be in someone else's shoes.
It is hard to be\nadmitted that even
the most well-meaning\nand sensitive
find it hard to imagine what\nthe suffocation, darkness,
and sheer physical\nsuffering of being
at the bottom of a social\nhierarchy might really be like.
The very thing you would\nexpect to instigate
questions of justice makes\nit hard to even raise them."
And so it really is a\nvery difficult problem
to be engaged with.
