So I think for me, working--\njust to summarize--
is working in Mumbai,\nin India, is about
negotiating these global flows\nthat do not erase and remake
landscapes, but rather to occupy\nthese local fissures to create
fascinating hybrids\nthat I believe.
And I think softening\nthese thresholds
between constituent\ngroups and your approach
to the models of practice is,\nI think, an interesting way
to engage with this.
The question for architects\nand conservationists,
urban designers, landscape\narchitects, planners,
is can we design for\nthis space of blur?
Can we design with\na divided mind?
Can be, more\nimportantly, be inspired
by the design\nintelligence of this kind
of particular condition to act\nand intervene as designers,
activists in our own locality?
Can we design to construct\nsoft thresholds that
facilitate porosity\nsocially and spatially?
So our approach has, in this\ncontext of our democracy,
been to do just that.
I believe this is a\npractice of democracy.
And it doesn't give you\nnecessarily the most consistent
visual images, which I\nthink Mohsen picked up
on very insightfully.
But it allows you to engage in\nthese multiple kinds of ways.
Because a pluralistic\nsociety is one
that not only accepts\ndifferences but goes
beyond to understand\nand is influenced by it
in productive ways.
That is to see the simultaneous\nvalidity of difference.
Because once the\narchitect and planner sees
these various differences\nas being valid,
the challenge is how to go\nbeyond their polarized binaries
through the making\nof architecture,
soft thresholds, spaces that\nare visually, physically porous,
plural in spirit and\nexpression, and most important
and critically encompassing\nof the context.
This is truly, I think, the\naspiration of our practice.
We are aware that many of the\nconditions that I've described
are emblematic of the\nissues and the crises,
really, that we are facing in\nmany parts of the globe, crises
within the profession,\nbut also crises
in the contemporary world\nthat we collectively occupy.
And I think understanding\nthis crisis and the condition
of crisis and articulating it\nin terms that are useful for us
to designers is an absolute\ncrucial first step.
Because after all, as Paul\nRomer from the World Bank said,
he said, a crisis is a\nterrible thing to waste.
